{{Infobox islands | name = Ruin Island | image_name = Ruin Island with Cape Russell in Background.jpg | image_caption = Ruin Island with Cape Russell in Background | image_size = | map = Greenland | map_caption = Ruin Island (Greenland) | native_name = | native_name_link = | nickname = | location = Greenland | coordinates = {{coord|78|52.1|N|69|11.3|W|region:CA_type:isle_scale:8000000|display=inline,title|name=Ruin Island}} | archipelago = | total_islands = | major_islands = | area_km2 = | length_km = | width_km = | rank = | highest_mount = | elevation_m= | country = Greenland | country_admin_divisions_title = [[Greenland]] | country_admin_divisions = | country_largest_city = | country_largest_city_population = | country_leader_title = | country_leader_name = | population = | population_as_of = | density_km2 = | ethnic_groups = | additional_info = }}
'''Ruin Island''' is a small island off the coast of the [[Inglefield Land]] region of northwest [[Greenland]]. In the 1930s, Danish archaeologist [[Erik Holtved]] discovered the remains of human habitation on the island. The culture associated with this archaeological site became known as the Ruin Island phase of [[Thule Culture]].<ref>Archaeology of Prehistoric Native America: An Encyclopedia. Gibbon, Guy E. and Kenneth M. Ames. 1998</ref> Vikings travelled to Ruin Island while hunting and trading with [[Inuit]] groups.<ref>Inuit-Norse contact in the Smith Sound region/Schledermann, P. McCullough, K.M.</ref>
==History==
The earliest known inhabitants of Ruin Island are ancestors of the Inuit known as Thule culture, named after the nearby archeologic site of Thule. These Thule culture inhabitants have been estimated to arrive at Ruin Island between 1280 and 1330.<ref>The Northern World: AD 900–1400. Edited by Herbert Maschner, Owen Mason, and Robert McGhee. 2009</ref>
