{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2015}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Russell Stone | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1923|04|07|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]] | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | fields = History | workplaces = [[University of Auckland]] | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = University of Auckland | thesis_title = Auckland business and businessmen in the 1880s | thesis_url = | thesis_year = 1969 | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = History of Auckland | influences = | influenced = | awards = | spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }} '''Russell Cyril James Stone''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|ONZM|size=85%}} (born 7 April 1923)<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaster|first1=Adrian|title=The international authors and writers who's who|date=1977|publisher=International Biographical Centre|isbn=090033245X|page=984}}</ref> is a New Zealand historian,<ref>{{cite news |title=A place apart |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10666443 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=23 August 2010 |accessdate=14 March 2012 }}</ref> author and professor emeritus at the [[University of Auckland]]. He is the leading authority on the [[history of Auckland]] and has written nine books on early [[Auckland]] history.<ref>{{cite news |title=Auckland's historic treasure |first=John |last=Roughan |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10837282 |newspaper=The New Zealand Herald |date=29 September 2012 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>
Born in the Auckland suburb of [[Mount Eden]] in 1923,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=AS19230410.2.3 | title=Births | date=10 April 1923 | work=[[Auckland Star]] | accessdate=19 April 2015 | page=1}}</ref> Stone graduated from [[University of Auckland|Auckland University College]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in 1945 and an [[Master of Arts|MA]] with first-class honours in 1949.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://shadowsoftime.co.nz/university22.html |title=NZ university graduates 1870–1961: Sl–Sz |date= |website= |publisher= |accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> After working as a secondary-school teacher, Stone was appointed to the staff of the history department at the University of Auckland in 1964,<ref name="Scoop">{{cite news | url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/ED0404/S00028/emeritus-professors-history-wins-biennial-prize.htm | title=Emeritus professor's history wins biennial prize | date=8 April 2004 | work=Scoop Independent News | accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> and completed a PhD in history in 1969. His thesis was titled ''Auckland business and businessmen in the 1880s''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://librarysearch.auckland.ac.nz/UOA2_A:uoa_alma21190927750002091 |title=Library search |date= |website= |publisher=University of Auckland |accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> He retired in 1989 and was granted the title of professor emeritus.<ref>{{cite book |title=University of Auckland Calendar 1992 |url=http://www.calendar.auckland.ac.nz/archive/1992-calendar.pdf |accessdate=19 April 2015 |page=19}}</ref>
In 1881 [[John Logan Campbell]]'s memoirs were published, and Stone republished these long out-of-print tales in his book: ''Poenamo: Romance and Reality of Antipodean Life in the Infancy of a New Colony''. Stone had earlier written a two-volume life of John Logan Campbell: * ''Young Logan Campbell'' (1982)<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.press.auckland.ac.nz/en/browse-books/all-books/books-1982/Young-Logan-Campbell.html | title=Young Logan Campbell | publisher=Auckland University Press | author=Stone, R. C. J. | year=1982 | pages=286 | isbn=9780196480190}}</ref> * ''The Father and his Gift: John Logan Campbell's Later Years'' (1987)<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.press.auckland.ac.nz/en/browse-books/all-books/books-1982/Young-Logan-Campbell.html | title=The Father and his Gift: John Logan Campbell's Later Years | publisher=Auckland University Press | author=Stone, R. C. J. | year=1987 | pages=310 | isbn=9781869400163}}</ref>
In the [[2002 New Year Honours]] Stone was appointed an [[New Zealand Order of Merit|Officer of the New Zealand Order of Merit]] for services to historical research.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/node/385 |title=New Year honours list 2002 |date=31 December 2001 |publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> He was the joint winner of the biennial J.M. Sherrard Award in New Zealand local and regional history in 2004, for his book ''From Tamaki-Makau-rau to Auckland'', published in 2001.<ref name="Scoop"/>
== Personal life == Stone has three children, and two grandchildren.
